It appears there is an MemorySanitizer error in iverilog:
```
==618489==WARNING: MemorySanitizer: use-of-uninitialized-value
    #0 0x621135 in NetNet::get_module_port_index() const .../iverilog/netlist.cc:689:7
    #1 0x6c1c53 in dll_target::signal(NetNet const*) .../iverilog/t-dll.cc:2611:38
    #2 0x5b57c4 in NetScope::emit_scope(target_t*) const .../iverilog/emit.cc:442:11
    #3 0x5b5725 in NetScope::emit_scope(target_t*) const .../iverilog/emit.cc:438:19
    #4 0x5b5fed in Design::emit(target_t*) const .../iverilog/emit.cc:528:16
    #5 0x5da712 in main .../iverilog/main.cc:1225:30
```

This can be fixed by initializing the port_index_ field to some default value in the constructors for NetNet. If a default value is not sensible, I'd advise using `std::optional<int>` rather than `int` for the type of `port_index_`.

The issue should be reproducible by compiling iverilog under msan (compile with clang and `CXXFLAGS="-fsanitize=memory -fsanitize-memory-track-origins -fno-omit-frame-pointer -g" LDFLAGS="-fsanitize=memory"`) and running it on the following Verilog file.
However, when I ran this on a git checkout of iverilog, it ran into other msan errors before running into that one, and I did not have time to track down their root cause; I originally ran into the bug in a modified version 10.2 of the iverilog that we use in Google. I double checked and the issue appears to exist in the source code of the master branch here however.

